INSERT INTO `couch_data_text` VALUES("8", "18", "<h4>\r\n	Kinship families</h4>\r\n<p>\r\n	The Kincare Support Program serves kinship families. These are families where a relative caregiver&mdash;usually a grandmother&mdash;is the primary caregiver of children under age 18. Many of the children have ended up in these situations through traumatic experiences, such as the death, incarceration, or substance abuse of a parent. Kinship families often struggle with the impact of trauma on children as well as poverty and issues related to aging for the caregivers. Many kinship providers report losing their friends and social networks once they become primary caregivers again&mdash;a situation that can lead to feelings of alienation and profound loss. The Kincare Support Program links these families to services and provides support so that the caregivers can be effective parents to their young children.</p>\r\n", "Kinship families The Kincare Support Program serves kinship families. These are families where a relative caregiver—usually a grandmother—is the primary caregiver of children under age 18. Many of the children have ended up in these situations through traumatic experiences, such as the death, incarceration, or substance abuse of a parent. Kinship families often struggle with the impact of trauma on children as well as poverty and issues related to aging for the caregivers. Many kinship providers report losing their friends and social networks once they become primary caregivers again—a situation that can lead to feelings of alienation and profound loss. The Kincare Support Program links these families to services and provides support so that the caregivers can be effective parents to their young children.");
INSERT INTO `couch_data_text` VALUES("8", "25", "<h4>\r\n	A larger trend with proven results</h4>\r\n<p>\r\n	Kinship care is one of the fastest growing trends in the child welfare system and&mdash;as an alternative to non-kin foster placements&mdash;can lead to improved outcomes for children. For example, according to a study by the Annie E. Casey Foundation, kinship care helps keep families together, provides a more stable alternative for children, and helps utilize and preserve cultural values, especially for children of color. Additionally, children in kinship homes have fewer behavioral problems, are less likely to reenter care after they&rsquo;ve gone home or been adopted, and are three to four times less likely to be maltreated than children in traditional foster homes. A Johns Hopkins study reported that having grandparents as caregivers reduces the risk of childhood injury (the leading cause of death for children) by about half. By conservative estimates, kinship caregivers save taxpayers more than $6.5 billion per year in federal foster care costs.</p>\r\n", "A larger trend with proven results Kinship care is one of the fastest growing trends in the child welfare system and—as an alternative to non-kin foster placements—can lead to improved outcomes for children. For example, according to a study by the Annie E. Casey Foundation, kinship care helps keep families together, provides a more stable alternative for children, and helps utilize and preserve cultural values, especially for children of color. Additionally, children in kinship homes have fewer behavioral problems, are less likely to reenter care after they’ve gone home or been adopted, and are three to four times less likely to be maltreated than children in traditional foster homes. A Johns Hopkins study reported that having grandparents as caregivers reduces the risk of childhood injury (the leading cause of death for children) by about half. By conservative estimates, kinship caregivers save taxpayers more than $6.5 billion per year in federal foster care costs.");
