INSERT INTO `couch_fulltext` VALUES("8", "Default page for kincare.php * PLEASE CHANGE THIS TITLE *", "Kinship families The Kincare Support Program serves kinship families. These are families where a relative caregiver—usually a grandmother—is the primary caregiver of children under age 18. Many of the children have ended up in these situations through traumatic experiences, such as the death, incarceration, or substance abuse of a parent. Kinship families often struggle with the impact of trauma on children as well as poverty and issues related to aging for the caregivers. Many kinship providers report losing their friends and social networks once they become primary caregivers again—a situation that can lead to feelings of alienation and profound loss. The Kincare Support Program links these families to services and provides support so that the caregivers can be effective parents to their young children. A larger trend with proven results Kinship care is one of the fastest growing trends in the child welfare system and—as an alternative to non-kin foster placements—can lead to improved outcomes for children. For example, according to a study by the Annie E. Casey Foundation, kinship care helps keep families together, provides a more stable alternative for children, and helps utilize and preserve cultural values, especially for children of color. Additionally, children in kinship homes have fewer behavioral problems, are less likely to reenter care after they’ve gone home or been adopted, and are three to four times less likely to be maltreated than children in traditional foster homes. A Johns Hopkins study reported that having grandparents as caregivers reduces the risk of childhood injury (the leading cause of death for children) by about half. By conservative estimates, kinship caregivers save taxpayers more than $6.5 billion per year in federal foster care costs. Want more information? For more information, contact our Family Center at 206-772-2050. Stories of our clients Taking care of herself to take care of others - Ms. Smith   She is raising her 8 year old grandson, and her 13 and 14 year old granddaughters. Ms. Smith is 72 years of age and came to the support group because of a friend sharing about what RAYS has to offer kinship caregivers. She had moved and could no longer attend her previous group but was in desperate need of support. She is raising her 8 year old grandson, and her 13 and 14 year old granddaughters. Ms. Smith had several health challenges, including diabetes and high blood pressure. She was constantly at the doctor, as her health concerns were spiraling out of control. She was told that she had to change her diet and the ways she cooked.   Ms. Smith is not alone in her challenges. The RAYS Kinship Care Support group has over 30 members, many of whom have their own health issues. In response to this the group facilitator planned for speakers in the medical field to come in and present on a number of topics, including: diabetes, high blood pressure, ways to relieve stress, and how to improve your diet. RAYS also hosted an 8 week class on “Living Well with Chronic Illnesses” given by Group Health.   Other group members now look to Ms. Smith as a resource, and continue to ask her questions about what and how she made the changes. Through the presenters and Ms. Smith&#039;s permanent doctor talking with her she made many positive changes in her healthcare routine. She was so proud of herself when she told the support group that because of changing the way she cooked her food and what she ate she no longer had to take insulin shots. Other group members now look to Ms. Smith as a resource, and continue to ask her questions about what and how she made the changes. Because of cooking and eating healthier she has brightened her future and increased her quality of life, enabling her to better raise her grandchildren.   *Name changed for confidentiality purposes. ");
INSERT INTO `couch_fulltext` VALUES("9", "Default page for healthystart.php * PLEASE CHANGE THIS TITLE *", "Want more information? For more information, contact our Family Center at 206-772-2050. Strengthening young families Healthy Start is a home-visiting program designed to promote the health and success of children in young families, from pregnancy to birth, and through their first years as new parents. Families enrolled in the program receive parenting education, along with group support, developmental and health screenings, and referrals to needed resources within their community. Healthy Start is a collaboration between Friends of Youth, the Center for Human Services, Northshore Youth &amp; Family Services, Youth Eastside Services, and RAYS. Growing up - Margaret Healthy Start at RAYS has completely changed my life as a parent and as an adult. The program has helped greatly increase my confidence and self esteem. I have received resources that improved the quality of my life and my son&#039;s life. The material items as well as the community resources and one on one support helped to take away some of the constant stress of being a young, single parent, so that I can be more loving and patient with my son.   &quot;I began to feel overwhelmed with the responsibility of parenting and underwhelmed by lack of encouragement&quot; Before I was being mentored, I did not believe I could thrive on my own or that I would be a sucessful parent. When I came into the program, I thought I had enough support from family and friends. As my son was about three months old, I began to feel overwhelmed with the responsibility of parenting and underwhelmed by lack of encouragement from the people around me. From the very first meeting with my Family Support Specialist, Karina, she made me feel comfortable and capable. She pointed out my strengths and told me about all the things I was doing right. She complimented me and made me feel important. I realized that I had bee missing this kind of support in my life.   Not only did Karina help me with my immediate needs, such as clothing, diapers, wipes, toys for son, but she also helped me to find housing. She asked me if I would like to be more independent, and she helped me to gain the skills and confidence requried to live on my own. I was able to get into transitional housing, and now I am in permanent housing through King County. I am so grateful for the opportunity to get into a stable housing program so that I no longer have to rely on family or a roommate to afford a safe and nice place to live.   &quot;I had someone helping me along the way to help me develop a special bond with my son&quot; I have learned and grown so much as a parent through the curriculum at Healthy Start. It has been very helpful to learn about my son&#039;s development every month and have activities to do with him that I know will benefit him. I feel fortunate that I had someone helping me along the way to help me develop a special bond with my son. In addition to parenting skills, I have also learned life skills such as money management, which have been extremely beneficial in my life.   Since being in the Healthy Start program, I have been living on my own for almost two years. I recently graduated with honors from Bellevue College with my Associates in Arts and Sciences, and I have been accepted into a reputable internship program in my church. I am living with confidence that I can try new things and succeed life because I have had the opportunity to grow and be successful in what I have done so far. *Name changed for confidentiality purposes. Healthy Start participants at a Gymboree event, 2011. ");
INSERT INTO `couch_fulltext` VALUES("10", "Default page for mentalhealth.php * PLEASE CHANGE THIS TITLE *", "Stories of our clients Keeping going - Ashley, 16 Ashley was referred to RAYS after experiencing a sexual assault at the age of 10, and winding her way through a number of professionals and programs. Ashley struggled with change, having lacked consistency with who she worked with and being obligated to tell her story again and again to different people. Battling with severe depression, Ashley was actively suicidal and had been hospitalized in the past. “She was going through the impact of trauma, and not feeling supported by her family.” Her counselor noted that “she was going through the impact of trauma, and not feeling supported by her family.” Hearing from both peers and family the idea that she essentially had to “deal with this on her own”, getting the support that she needed from her mom in particular had proven to be a struggle.   When asked what was her biggest success in counseling with RAYS, she replied that “she’s alive still.” Ashley credited much of that fact to the skills she had learned through counseling, not the least of which were journaling and free writing. ...she replied that “she’s alive still.” Through writing and addressing the underlying belief structure she had developed around the trauma, Ashley has been able to better calm herself down when she is feeling reactive, and ultimately be more authentic in who she is.   Recently Ashley has continued to work on her communication, and to confront the difficulty she finds in being alone. She is taking initiative to overcome her depression and apathy, and her counselor has noted just how exciting it is “starting to see her thrive, and really, not needing counseling anymore.” *Name changed for confidentiality purposes. Want more information? For more information regarding our mental health services, contact our main office at 425-271-5600. From one heart to another - Julia, 2nd grade Julia was referred to our counseling team by her mom and teacher who were both concerned about her self- esteem. Julia has ADHD and struggles with impulse control, which can make it hard to learn, and hard to make friends. She had fallen behind academically and socially, and at her first meeting with her therapist cried in her office asking: &quot;Why is it so much harder for me to make a friend than everyone else?&quot;   On her own she recognized her distress, gave her lots of encouragement, and helped her problem solve. For six months Julia and her therapist worked on friendship skills, identifying her strengths and helping her learn to think positive thoughts about herself. She is attending a summer social skills camp at a Tukwila elementary school, and has quickly formed a bond with another girl who has similar difficulties. In fact on the first day of &quot;RAYS Camp&quot;, Julia showed remarkable empathy when her new friend became frustrated during an art activity. On her own she recognized her distress, gave her lots of encouragement, and helped her problem solve. Her therapist remarked that &quot;Julia has the biggest heart I&#039;ve ever encountered in such a young person, and it was a thrill to see her use some of the skills we&#039;ve been practicing to help a friend. &quot;   For more than 40 years RAYS has worked with youth and their families to overcome challenges, build healthier habits, and more beneficial relationships. Through one-on- one counseling, or communication with the whole family, RAYS helps its clients build the capacity to improve their own circumstances. We believe in a hollistic approach considering the needs of all members of the family, while never forgetting that it is the child-caregiver relationship that is our primary client. We believe that everyone can recover, if they are just have the tools to do so. At RAYS we celebrate both small and large victories alike, because change can be difficult. RAYS serves primarily high- needs families, and provides referrals to other services and organizations when they are needed. By building skills that help today, we believe that our communities will be stronger tomorrow. Our expertise RAYS has extensive experience in working with people of extremely diverse circumstances and cultural backgrounds. We&#039;ve worked with all kinds of familial situations, including foster families, grandparents raising grandchildren, and homes of relative placements. Our staff includes master&#039;s level trained therapists and bachelor&#039;s level trained case managers with significant experience with a broad range of issues including, but not limited to: Behavioral problems Anger management Domestic violence &amp; child abuse Child abuse prevention Depression Grief &amp; loss Our services RAYS works closely with families and communities to build on strengths and improve the emotional and behavioral health of youth of all ages, in a wide variety of settings. RAYS Summer Activity Program, 2013. ");
