INSERT INTO `jstitch_posts` VALUES("25", "1", "2013-09-09 01:43:37", "2013-09-09 01:43:37", "As a single dad raising a little boy, I designed the j-stitch vest as an alternative to lugging around a traditional blue-flowered diaper bag. Designing and working in my independent studio gave me an opportunity to raise my son at home. Carrying his own gear in the j-stitch vest gave my kid a sense that he was helping.\r\n\r\nTwenty years later, Quinn (live link) is a graduate of NYU’s Tisch whatever, and he still carries his own gear.\r\n\r\npress\r\n\r\npdf of presskit: “About the Designer”, awards and distinctions.\r\n\r\n“About the Designer”\r\n\r\nJerry Gundersen was born and raised by wolves in a nice family in Seattle. His mom wore cat’s eye glasses and read books, and his dad made signs, drank beer and played cribbage. As a kid, Jerry was always making forts, clothes and messes. At his grandmother’s knee, he learned to make jam, and to use the iron for making grilled cheese sandwiches.\r\n\r\nEventually, Jerry learned to sew like the wind, to design apparel and make patterns. He has designed everything from couture wedding gowns to seam-sealed Gore-Tex outerwear. He is the founder of Point White Design, a freelance firm based in Bainbridge Island, Washington. Jerry loves hiking, biking, dogs, little kids, popcorn and grilled cheese sandwiches. He also enjoys Vespa scooters, British fashion and novels by his favorite author (link <a href=\"http://www.susanwiggs.com/\">www.susanwiggs.com</a>). His favorite designer is Paul Smith, his favorite scotch is Lagavulin and his favorite color is usually navy blue. In his spare time, he turns waste vegetable oil into biodiesel to fuel his car and heat his house.\r\n\r\nfor fun (shit Carter says)", "About", "", "inherit", "closed", "open", "", "19-revision-v1", "", "", "2013-09-09 01:43:37", "2013-09-09 01:43:37", "", "19", "http://localhost/jstitch/wordpress/?p=25", "0", "revision", "", "0");
